# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1911-new-york-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] The **1911 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 29th season.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] The Giants won their first of three consecutive National League pennants.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] They were defeated by the Philadelphia Athletics in the World Series.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] The team set and still holds the Major League Baseball single-season record for stolen bases during the modern era (since 1901), with 347.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] Led by manager John McGraw, the Giants won the National League pennant by 7+1⁄2 games.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] On the offensive side, they finished second in runs scored.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] On the defensive side, they allowed the fewest.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] Hall of Famer Christy Mathewson led the league in earned run average, and Rube Marquard had the most strikeouts.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] The Giants hit 103 triples, the most in franchise history.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] One of the Giants' drawing cards came in the form of unknown pitcher Charlie Faust, whose story was retold by Fred Snodgrass in *The Glory of Their Times*.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] Faust was considered something of a "good-luck charm" by manager McGraw, and was used sparingly.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] In 1911, Faust appeared in just two games for the team, which was the entirety of his major league playing career.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] As a pitcher, he pitched two innings, giving up one run.
[src:1911-new-york-giants-season/1911-new-york-giants-season] As a batter, he tallied one hit by pitch, two stolen bases, and one run scored, in zero at bats.
